h3. Issue Summary

For Mobile Apps, when SAML uses NTLM auth method, it fails with the following error message at the logs:
{code}
 [2020-04-14 20:36:07 +0000]: AuthWebViewController.handle(challengeType:protectionSpace:completion:) challengeType: unsupported("NSURLAuthenticationMethodNTLM")).
{code}

Only basic auth is supported by mobile apps.

 

Our documentation at
 [Confluence Mobile|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/confluence-mobile-284365706.html] states:
{quote}
h4. *Login and authentication*

The app supports all common Confluence user management configurations, including external user directories and SAML single sign-on. Users will need to sign in to use the app, even if your site allows anonymous access.  
{quote}
But it does not mention that we do have restrictions for NTLM.

h3. Problem

Jira can't locate Confluence page that contains ":"
h3. Environment
* Confluence 7.2.1
* Jira 8.1.0

h3. Steps to Reproduce
h5. In Confluence
 # Create a page that has ":" in the title
 !1.png|thumbnail! 
 # Copy the Page URL
 ** [http://puvenm.com/confluence/display/721/PM-1%3ATest+Page]

h5. In Jira
 # Create a Story
 # At the Story, click on *More* > *Link*
 # Click on *Confluence Page* and add the Confluence page URL
 !3.png|thumbnail! 
 # Click on *Link
 !2.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Expected Results
 [^CSP-272805_2.webm] 
h3. Actual Results
 [^CSP-272805_1.webm] 

h3. Workaround
h5. _Nginx_
{code:java}
location /<context-path> {

    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Server $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for; 
 
if ($request_uri ~* "/<context-path>(/.*)") { 
	proxy_pass http://<base-url>/<context-path>$1; break; 
}

proxy_pass http://<base-url>/<context-path>;
} {code}
h5. Apache
{code:java}
ProxyPass /confluence http://localhost:8090/confluence nocanon {code}
h3. Notes

h3. Issue Summary

If a page is created via the REST API {{rest/api/content/}} and its content contain empty paragraph tags, the page will not have any line breaks when viewing. However when the page is open for editing and closed even without any change, paragraphs with a line break, {{<p><br /></p>}}, are inserted to the storage format in place of the empty paragraph tags.
 This means a different behaviour between first *Viewing* a page and after first *Editing* a page.

As it is specified for the [paragraph <p> tag|https://www.w3docs.com/learn-html/html-p-tag.html]:
{quote}The <p> tag defines a paragraph of text. It is a block-level element and always starts on a new line.
{quote}
So the empty paragraph tags should already be replaced with {{<p><br /></p>}} when page is created from the REST API.

Examples of empty paragraph tags:
 * {{<p></p>}}
 * {{<p />}}
 * {{<p> (any number of whitespaces) </p>}}
 * {{<p><span></span></p>}}
 * {{<p class="(a class name)"></p>}}
 * {{<p class="(a class name)" />}}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page via REST API using the example:
{noformat}
curl -u admin:admin -X POST -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"type":"page","title":"3 lines with empty paragraphs","space":{"key":"TST"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>These three lines</p><p>      </p><p>should have no space</p><p /><p>between them</p>","representation":"storage"}}}' http://localhost:8080/confluence/rest/api/content/
 {noformat}

 # Open the page in Confluence;
 # Edit the page but don't make any change;
 # Click on *Update*.

h3. Expected Results

The page should be displayed the same in Step 2 and after Step 4.
h3. Actual Results

The page is displayed with no empty lines in Step 2, as seen in
 !3-Lines-v1.png|thumbnail!
 The storage format for page's v1 is:
{noformat}
<p>These three lines</p>
<p>      </p>
<p>should have no space</p> 
<p>between them</p>
{noformat}
 

After Step 4 the page is displayed with empty lines in between, as seen in
 !3-Lines-v2.png|thumbnail!
 The storage format for current version is:
{noformat}
<p>These three lines</p>
<p><br /></p>
<p>should have no space</p>
<p><br /></p>
<p>between them</p>
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no other workaround to prevent this behaviour, except not having empty paragraph tags (any variation) in the content passed to the REST API.

After adding pages via the REST API, you can run SQL statements to replace the empty paragraphs with either:
 * a whitespace - this will prevent the empty lines to be added after editing;
 * with the tags {{<p><br /></p>}} - this replicates the Editor behaviour and is the ideal option as an paragraph tag should always mean a new line.

Below you'll find SQL statements for the example page given above:
{code:sql}
UPDATE bodycontent SET body = REPLACE(body,'<p>      </p>'),' ') WHERE body LIKE concat('%<p>      </p>%');

UPDATE bodycontent SET body = REPLACE(body,'<p />','<p><br /></p>') WHERE body LIKE '%<p />%';
{code}
